article.description: Mandi Moore and Jordan Adams carried the Lobos to an OT win over upset-minded Miami.
article.headline: Moore and Adams lead Lobos through the Hurricanes
article.linkText: New Mexico goes OT to win first NCAA tourney game
article.story:
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- The New Mexico Lobos were 25 minutes
late for their party in The Pit, but guard Mandi Moore and center
Jordan Adams made sure once they arrived, they partied in style.

	   Moore's second-half 3-point shooting and Adams' 27 points and
eight blocks carried the Lobos to a 91-85 overtime victory over Miami
Saturday in the Midwest Regional, the Lobos' first triumph ever in the
NCAA Tournament.

	   New Mexico (23-8) advances to play Mississippi State (25-7) in
the second round Monday. Mississippi State beat Manhattan 73-47.

	   Moore hit four 3-pointers to spark a 17-6 run by the Lobos in
the second half that rallied New Mexico from a 40-29 halftime
deficit. Her last 3-pointer cut the Miami lead to 55-52 with 11:43
left.

	   The victory was before a crowd of 16,151, the largest ever to see a
first-round women's game in the NCAA Tournament.

	   Adams scored 18 points in the second half, while Moore and
Chelsea Grear each scored 18 in the game. Moore got 16 of hers in
the second half.

	   Freshman Tamara James led the Hurricanes with 23 points and
Yalonda McCormick scored 20.

	   Miami dominated for the game's first 25 minutes and New Mexico's
comeback started with a short baseline jumper by Moore that made it
49-37 Miami with 15 minutes left.

	   ''Things weren't going well for us and we were definitely in a
drought,'' Moore said. ''Nothing was really working for us, so when
I hit the little jumper, I started feeling good. It all took off
from there.''

	   New Mexico and Miami (18-13) both had a chance to win it in
regulation. Adams missed three free throws in the final 46 seconds,
including two with 8.9 seconds left.

	   After the second miss, Miami (18-13) got the ball up the court,
but McCormick's off-balance 14-footer with two seconds left was an
airball.

	   New Mexico took control in the overtime on five free throws by
Adams, Cristal Garcia and Grear. Adams also hit a layup and a
14-footer to put the Lobos up 87-79 with 1:36 remaining.

	   ''We felt at halftime that we could close the gap a little at a
time and gradually get control of the game,'' New Mexico coach Don
Flanagan said. ''If we could do that, we felt the crowd would be a
factor.''

	   Moore's shooting caught the Hurricanes by surprise.

	   ''She really wasn't a threat to us in the beginning of the
game,'' James said.

	   Miami coach Ferne Labati said her team played well but couldn't
hold off the Lobos' rally and overcome New Mexico's homecourt edge.

	   ''My kids played with their hearts. They never gave up,'' Labati
said. ''The crowd was a factor.''

	   New Mexico trailed 49-35 after McCormick scored underneath. New
Mexico, which had struggled against the Hurricanes' quickness
throughout the first half, suddenly caught fire. And it was Moore
who got it started and the crowd followed her lead.

	   With Moore hitting 3s from the top of the key, New Mexico cut
the deficit to 55-52 with 11:43 remaining. A 3-pointer by Lauren
McLeod gave New Mexico its first lead of the game at 62-61.
McLeod's baseline shot sent Moore screaming with glee up the court
and came in the midst of an 11-0 run that put the Lobos up 69-61
with 4:44 left.

	   But Miami, the No. 11 seed, battled back to force overtime as
James scored 10 points over the final 3:34. James scored on
offensive rebound with 29 seconds left to give Miami a 77-76 lead,
but Garcia was fouled with 16.3 seconds left and hit the first of
two free throws.

	   Adams got a hand on Garcia's missed free throw and tipped back
to Garcia. Adams then was fouled but missed both foul shots.
